field_reports.description:
Since February 5, heavy rainfall has affected Lankaran city and surrounding areas, leading to flooding in several districts, including Girdani, Kosalar, and Shilavar villages. The rainfall reached up to 133 mm, overwhelming drainage systems and causing water accumulation in streets and residential areas.

Impact:

  • Streets in Lankaran city center were severely flooded, disrupting transportation.
  • Several houses and agricultural lands were affected by the flooding.
  • A total of 22 people, including 6 children, were evacuated due to rising water levels.

Response Actions:

  • The Ministry of Emergency Situations (MES) deployed response teams, including the South Regional Center, State Fire Protection Service, and Special Risk Rescue Service.
  • Rescue operations and water drainage efforts are ongoing in affected areas.
  • Heavy machinery has been mobilized to clear blocked drainage channels.
  • Local authorities ensure uninterrupted supply of essential services, including gas, electricity, and daily necessities.

Current Status:

  • The Lankaran Emergency Commission is working in an enhanced mode to coordinate response efforts.
  • The local administration is monitoring the situation, and authorities continue evacuation and flood mitigation activities in affected areas.

field_reports.description:
Heavy rainfall and excessive flooding in the Hajigabul district have caused significant damage in the area.

According to Saleh Alasgarov, the chairman of the Hajigabul District Emergency Commission, who provided information, the natural disaster in Hajigabul began in the afternoon. Due to the heavy floods originating from Mount Mushov and the intense rainfall, there was a disruption in electricity supply to the city center. In addition to the district center, more than 300 households in the villages of "Qubalı Baloğlan", "Pirsaat", "Udulu", "Nəvahi", and "Qızılburun" were flooded.

Traffic on the city’s internal roads became difficult. Furthermore, the Shirvan-Hajigabul railway was affected by the floodwaters caused by the heavy downpour. Currently, around 50 different types of machinery and personnel have been deployed to the area to mitigate the damage.

field_reports.description:
Due to torrential rains, floodwaters filled the courtyards, basements and first floors of more than 100 houses in Zagatala, and four bridges were damaged.

The torrential rains, which started in the evening on the 17th, continued until the night of September 18. The area of Car and Yukhari Tala villages of the district was flooded. Several trees fell due to strong wind. Due to the torrential rains that fell on the mountainous and foothills of the region, the water in the Tala, Zilban, Bekmez and other rivers of the region has increased excessively. Tala, Zilban and Bekmez rivers were flooded for a short time. Three bridges in the area of Jar village and Gazangul settlement have become unusable due to the flood in the Bekmez river.

Due to the overflow of the Zilban river, the bridge in the part of the river passing through the territory of Zilban village has become unusable. Due to overflowing of the Tala river, the village of Yolayrj of the district was flooded.

field_reports.summary: AZE: Pluvial/Flash Flood - 2023-08 - Flooding in Goychay
field_reports.description:
As a result of heavy rains on August 26, 2023, a flash flood occurred in the villages of Garayazi, Garamaryam, Yekakhana, Ashaghi Garamaryam and Garabaggal of Goychay district. As a result of the flash flood, roads, electricity, natural gas, communication, drinking water lines, private households, cars, and other objects in the area were damaged.

A part of the road in the 194-205 kilometers of the M4 Baku-Shamakhi-Yevlakh highway, which passes through the territory of Garamaryam village of the region, has fallen into disrepair and traffic has been temporarily restricted. On August 27, 2023, the road was partially restored.

Also, in the area of the village of Ashagi Garamaryam, 3 automobile and 2 pedestrian bridges were blown up. As a result of flooding of the dump of household waste, located in the village of Garabakgal of the district, the waste scattered throughout the territory.

field_reports.description:
On August 02, 2023, as a result of the collapse of a part of the “Upper Karabakh” water channel of the Barda region of Azerbaijan, the village of Garagoyunlu of this region was flooded. The cause of the catastrophe was the rise of the water level in the canal as a result of heavy rain a few days ago.

The basements of about 65 houses and the houses of 30 houses were flooded. A large number of chickens, freshly harvested crops and melon plants were significantly damaged. As a result of the severe consequences of the flood, it became much more difficult for villagers to enter their homes or yards.

field_reports.description:
The flood was caused by the overflowing of the artificial lake in the city's park built on 12 hectares, which is more devastating than the previous floods that hit Ganja city in late May 2023.

Most of the houses based in the lower part of the park were damaged. The walls of most houses cracked, basements and backyards flooded with water.

As of June 23, more than 30 houses were damaged due to the flooding. A serious collapse has already been observed in the second concrete dam of the lake and as a result of unstable weather conditions (according to the information received from hydrometeorologists, heavy rains, hailstorms are expected in the next couple of days in the western regions of Azerbaijan, and the river waters in this region is expected to rise), the second dam is expected to collapse, which would dramatically increase the scale of the emergency.

Currently, the rescue teams of the Ganja Regional Center of the Ministry of Emergency Situations are carrying out high priority emergency work to reduce the water level in the lake. They are aiming at draining the water to prevent it from overflowing. Natural draining is not possible for the moment.

field_reports.summary: Escalation of the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict: Azerbaijan Red Crescent Society response
field_reports.description: Escalation of the conflict along the line of contact started in the morning of 27 September 2020. Civilian deaths and injuries, including of children, have been reported on the areas under Azerbaijani control. Habitats and civilian infrastructure are severely damaged.
